Besides this, the cunning slave—the character to whom the audience looked most confi· dently for amusement-could not be naturalised arnid Roman surroundings. Even on the stage at Athens he must have been considered an exaggeration, though an exaggeration in which the spectators could easily recognise the original. But at Rome, where the slave was looked upon as a mere chattel, he would have seemed not merely a parody, but an impossibility. lt would have been interesting indeed to watch the face of some stem master like Cato, while he was being treated by his slave with the impertinence which Stasimus shows to Callicles, or even with the friendly familiarity with which he receives Char· mides ou his return. lt was impossible, therefore, to give a genuine Roman colouring to Greek Comedy without sacrificing half the fun of it in the process.
